WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.036 --> 00:00:03.410
DAN: I met Fred
a couple of years

00:00:03.410 --> 00:00:05.130
ago, at the SF Green Festival.

00:00:05.130 --> 00:00:08.250
Amid the organic food and
soaps and different ways

00:00:08.250 --> 00:00:10.430
of using plastic, Fred
had something different,

00:00:10.430 --> 00:00:13.170
something which could
improve the lives of millions

00:00:13.170 --> 00:00:14.740
of poor people around the world.

00:00:14.740 --> 00:00:17.510
And I wanted to let Fred share
that idea with you today.

00:00:17.510 --> 00:00:21.550
Fred Colgan is the co-founder
of InStove, a nonprofit which

00:00:21.550 --> 00:00:23.920
is designing, building, and
distributing large, highly

00:00:23.920 --> 00:00:26.450
efficient cook stoves
in developing countries.

00:00:26.450 --> 00:00:30.790
He's joined by Assitan
Sylla Traore, Africa project

00:00:30.790 --> 00:00:32.460
coordinator at InStove.

00:00:32.460 --> 00:00:34.130
She is a Fulbright
scholar from Mali,

00:00:34.130 --> 00:00:36.410
with 18 years of
experience working

00:00:36.410 --> 00:00:39.430
with senior political and
diplomatic leaders in Mali.

00:00:39.430 --> 00:00:42.244
Please join me in
welcoming Fred and Assitan.

00:00:42.244 --> 00:00:43.285
FRED COLGAN: Thanks, Dan.

00:00:45.830 --> 00:00:47.520
Well, hi.

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:48.270
I'm Fred Colgan.

00:00:48.270 --> 00:00:52.570
I'm the executive director
and co-founder of InStove.

00:00:52.570 --> 00:00:55.890
Our full name is
Institutional Stove Solutions.

00:00:55.890 --> 00:00:59.720
We're a 501(c)3
non-profit organization,

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:03.140
and the manufacturer of clean
and efficient cook stoves

00:01:03.140 --> 00:01:07.492
and allied technologies
for the developing world.

00:01:07.492 --> 00:01:09.200
Now, when you think
of clean cook stoves,

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:14.390
you may think of some gleaming
new electric or gas range.

00:01:14.390 --> 00:01:17.320
And when you think of
institutional kitchens,

00:01:17.320 --> 00:01:20.200
you may think of the
fantastic workplaces

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:23.590
you see on celebrity
chef programs.

00:01:23.590 --> 00:01:26.310
But the reality in
the developing world

00:01:26.310 --> 00:01:29.400
is more like this.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:31.900
Chances are, your
last meal wasn't

00:01:31.900 --> 00:01:34.170
prepared over an open fire.

00:01:34.170 --> 00:01:38.470
But for about one out of
three people on Earth, it was.

00:01:38.470 --> 00:01:41.970
The cost of this is
staggering, globally.

00:01:41.970 --> 00:01:46.500
It leads to deforestation,
climate change, illness,

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:49.450
gender-based violence,
and even death.

00:01:49.450 --> 00:01:51.300
And the social costs
fall especially

00:01:51.300 --> 00:01:54.570
hard on the shoulders of
women and young girls,

00:01:54.570 --> 00:01:56.450
who do the cooking
and fuel gathering.

00:01:59.150 --> 00:02:03.610
2.7 billion people use
open fires to cook.

00:02:03.610 --> 00:02:07.630
Today, in sub-Saharan Africa,
which is our principle market,

00:02:07.630 --> 00:02:12.420
over 657 million people
use biomass fuels--

00:02:12.420 --> 00:02:17.090
like wood, charcoal, or
dung-- as a primary source

00:02:17.090 --> 00:02:18.680
of household energy.

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:22.000
While much of the planet is
moving away from this model,

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:25.770
in Africa, there are
multiple barriers-- political

00:02:25.770 --> 00:02:29.560
instability, corruption,
regional conflicts,

00:02:29.560 --> 00:02:32.660
all preventing many
from gaining access

00:02:32.660 --> 00:02:35.850
to electricity or
to modern fuels.

00:02:35.850 --> 00:02:38.390
The reality is that the
infrastructure simply

00:02:38.390 --> 00:02:42.650
is not enough to deliver
electricity and modern fuels.

00:02:42.650 --> 00:02:45.760
It's not growing fast
enough to meet demands,

00:02:45.760 --> 00:02:48.510
either current or projected.

00:02:48.510 --> 00:02:51.430
Every few years, the
International Energy Agency

00:02:51.430 --> 00:02:55.350
does an assessment of
energy use worldwide.

00:02:55.350 --> 00:02:57.670
They collect their
findings and analyses

00:02:57.670 --> 00:03:00.960
in a report called "The
World Energy Outlook."

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:07.110
I want to share one finding of
the IEA in their 2011 report.

00:03:07.110 --> 00:03:10.050
"While Africa's share
of the global population

00:03:10.050 --> 00:03:18.350
increases from 15% in 2009
to 20% percent in 2035,

00:03:18.350 --> 00:03:20.380
its share of global
energy demand

00:03:20.380 --> 00:03:25.950
declines fractionally to 5.4%
over the same time frame.

00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:31.700
Furthermore, 1/3 of the total
energy demand in Africa by 2035

00:03:31.700 --> 00:03:35.640
takes the form of
traditional biomass use."

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:38.560
In that same report,
the IEA projects

00:03:38.560 --> 00:03:41.310
that the number of people
in sub-Saharan Africa

00:03:41.310 --> 00:03:45.030
who will use biomass as
their primary source of fuel

00:03:45.030 --> 00:03:49.830
will be over 900
million people in 2035.

00:03:49.830 --> 00:03:51.610
That means, in
Africa, two decades

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:54.940
from now, the number of
people burning wood to cook

00:03:54.940 --> 00:03:57.910
will have grown by almost 50%.

00:03:57.910 --> 00:04:02.340
The environmental damage
from this is two-fold.

00:04:02.340 --> 00:04:06.320
First, the open-fire
cooking produces a long list

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:09.990
of noxious chemicals,
like benzene, and methane,

00:04:09.990 --> 00:04:11.520
and toluene.

00:04:11.520 --> 00:04:14.340
But the black carbon
and particulate matter

00:04:14.340 --> 00:04:17.850
is especially impactful
on climate change.

00:04:17.850 --> 00:04:21.600
It's estimated that open-fire
cooking in the world

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:24.130
produces more climate
change emissions

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:26.530
than the one billion
cars on the planet.

00:04:30.470 --> 00:04:34.600
Second, the unsustainable
harvesting of firewood

00:04:34.600 --> 00:04:37.080
destroys the very
forests that help

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:39.520
to mitigate climate change.

00:04:39.520 --> 00:04:41.980
On average, throughout
sub-Saharan Africa,

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:45.920
the level of deforestation
is between 3% to 4%

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:48.470
of existing forest each year.

00:04:48.470 --> 00:04:51.360
And in some regions,
like in northern Nigeria,

00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:56.870
that deforestation rate
climbs to over 11% per year.

00:04:56.870 --> 00:04:59.110
Deforestation brings
with it a cascade

00:04:59.110 --> 00:05:01.720
of environmental
and social problems

00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:04.690
that include acceleration
of desertification.

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:07.830
And the loss of watersheds,
the loss of habitat.

00:05:07.830 --> 00:05:13.220
And the loss of livelihoods the
depend on forest ecosystems.

00:05:13.220 --> 00:05:15.680
But the costs of
open-fire cooking

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:18.460
have a human dimension as well.

00:05:18.460 --> 00:05:21.370
The most recent global
burden of disease study,

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:24.240
published he asked last
year in "The Lancet,"

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:29.280
found that 4.3 million people
die each year from illnesses

00:05:29.280 --> 00:05:32.750
caused by exposure to
indoor air pollution.

00:05:32.750 --> 00:05:35.040
By way of comparison,
more people

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:40.390
die each year from cook smoke
than from HIV, AIDS, malaria,

00:05:40.390 --> 00:05:44.440
and tuberculosis combined.

00:05:44.440 --> 00:05:47.540
And this statistic does
not include those who die

00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:52.120
or become disfigured by burns
sustained while cooking.

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:55.830
This statistic does not include
the eye diseases-- including

00:05:55.830 --> 00:05:59.000
cataracts and macular
degeneration-- that

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.840
come from exposure to
indoor air pollution, which

00:06:01.840 --> 00:06:04.030
often lead to blindness.

00:06:04.030 --> 00:06:06.060
And this statistic
does not include

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:08.010
the gender-based
violence suffered

00:06:08.010 --> 00:06:11.740
by women and young girls
who cook outdoors, and trek

00:06:11.740 --> 00:06:15.460
long distances-- often through
dangerous territory-- in search

00:06:15.460 --> 00:06:18.250
of firewood together.

00:06:18.250 --> 00:06:20.450
These women and
girls must continue

00:06:20.450 --> 00:06:24.550
to go out because
gathering firewood is not

00:06:24.550 --> 00:06:27.860
only necessary for
their family's survival.

00:06:27.860 --> 00:06:31.180
It's often the only
income-generating activity

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:35.030
available to them,
especially in refugee camps

00:06:35.030 --> 00:06:39.100
and internally
displaced persons camps.

00:06:39.100 --> 00:06:42.570
When I went to Nyala
in Darfur in 2011,

00:06:42.570 --> 00:06:45.080
I was fortunate enough to
work with a large group

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:49.590
of African women who were cooks
in the schools in the camp.

00:06:49.590 --> 00:06:51.560
And after I gave a
demonstration at one camp,

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:54.210
a focus group of cooks
told me that they

00:06:54.210 --> 00:06:57.710
have to travel outside the
camp to gather firewood.

00:06:57.710 --> 00:07:00.310
And one out of every
three times they go out,

00:07:00.310 --> 00:07:01.435
they're sexually assaulted.

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:06.550
These problems are enormous.

00:07:06.550 --> 00:07:10.800
But at their root is a
solvable engineering problem.

00:07:10.800 --> 00:07:12.330
How do you design
a stove to make

00:07:12.330 --> 00:07:15.400
biomass cooking
more efficient, one

00:07:15.400 --> 00:07:17.460
that uses minimal
amounts of fuel,

00:07:17.460 --> 00:07:20.410
while producing minimal
amounts of emissions,

00:07:20.410 --> 00:07:24.080
and being safe for users?

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:27.590
In 2005, I wasn't
aware of most of this,

00:07:27.590 --> 00:07:30.180
though I had some
developing world experience.

00:07:30.180 --> 00:07:31.480
I was 60 years old.

00:07:31.480 --> 00:07:33.520
And my wife and
I moved to Oregon

00:07:33.520 --> 00:07:37.110
to retire to a little place
on the bank of the Willamette

00:07:37.110 --> 00:07:39.290
River in Oregon.

00:07:39.290 --> 00:07:42.190
I had planned to re-read
my science fiction

00:07:42.190 --> 00:07:45.110
library in my retirement years.

00:07:45.110 --> 00:07:49.130
But that plan
wasn't meant to be.

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:51.230
The property we bought
had an abandoned

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:53.750
slaughterhouse and
meat-packing plant on it.

00:07:53.750 --> 00:07:55.360
So I restored this building.

00:07:55.360 --> 00:08:00.110
And our first tenant was
Aprovecho Research Center.

00:08:00.110 --> 00:08:02.550
This is a nonprofit
research group

00:08:02.550 --> 00:08:06.080
that's been working for 30 years
on the design and development

00:08:06.080 --> 00:08:10.650
of clean-biomass cook stoves,
including the iconic rocket

00:08:10.650 --> 00:08:12.340
stove.

00:08:12.340 --> 00:08:17.040
And almost immediately at
Aprovecho, I met Damon Ogle.

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:20.270
Damon was a retired
mechanical engineer

00:08:20.270 --> 00:08:25.530
who had spent many years with a
successful independent business

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:28.280
with portable
rock-crushing mills,

00:08:28.280 --> 00:08:32.929
providing rock crushing to
government and mining clients

00:08:32.929 --> 00:08:34.789
throughout the Western US.

00:08:34.789 --> 00:08:36.600
Damon took an early retirement.

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:39.650
And he began looking for
ways to put his engineering

00:08:39.650 --> 00:08:43.039
experience to humanitarian use.

00:08:43.039 --> 00:08:46.400
Eventually, his interest in
water and sanitation systems

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:50.210
in the developing world
led him to Aprovecho,

00:08:50.210 --> 00:08:52.410
who were
world-recognized leaders

00:08:52.410 --> 00:08:56.070
in appropriate technology,
and within driving distance

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:57.500
for Damon.

00:08:57.500 --> 00:08:59.910
He joined Aprovecho
as a volunteer.

00:08:59.910 --> 00:09:02.780
And he began devoting the
second half of his life

00:09:02.780 --> 00:09:08.660
to using his engineering talents
to give back to humanity.

00:09:08.660 --> 00:09:12.420
After spending several years
of designing household stoves

00:09:12.420 --> 00:09:15.600
and implementing stove projects
throughout the developing

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:19.290
world, Damon began
focusing on building larger

00:09:19.290 --> 00:09:23.810
institutional rocket
stoves in places

00:09:23.810 --> 00:09:26.620
like refugee camps, and
schools, and hospitals,

00:09:26.620 --> 00:09:27.930
and rural clinics.

00:09:27.930 --> 00:09:31.950
Households stoves are simply
not sufficient to meet the need.

00:09:31.950 --> 00:09:35.530
These are institutions where
large quantities of food

00:09:35.530 --> 00:09:37.170
are prepared quickly.

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:40.980
This kind of cooking presents
different design challenges.

00:09:40.980 --> 00:09:44.490
But because of the
high level of fuel use

00:09:44.490 --> 00:09:47.620
and the high level of
resulting emissions,

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:49.510
Damon saw that when
you placed one improved

00:09:49.510 --> 00:09:53.390
institutional stove, the
impact is an order of magnitude

00:09:53.390 --> 00:09:58.350
higher than placing
a household stove.

00:09:58.350 --> 00:10:02.380
At Aprovecho, Damon learned
about the ten rocket stove

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:06.280
principles from their creator,
and our friend, Doctor Larry

00:10:06.280 --> 00:10:08.700
Winiarski.

00:10:08.700 --> 00:10:10.295
These ten principles
are as follows.

00:10:13.210 --> 00:10:17.110
First, insulate around the fire
with a low-mass, heat-resistant

00:10:17.110 --> 00:10:18.300
material.

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:21.610
The objective of this is to
create a refractive combustion

00:10:21.610 --> 00:10:22.560
chamber.

00:10:22.560 --> 00:10:27.170
The goal is not to heat the
stove, but to heat the pot.

00:10:27.170 --> 00:10:32.830
Number two, use an insulated,
upright, internal chimney

00:10:32.830 --> 00:10:36.350
immediately above the fire, to
promote mixing of the gases--

00:10:36.350 --> 00:10:39.025
the pyrolated gases-- and
to complete the combustion.

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:44.020
Number three, design
a stove to heat

00:10:44.020 --> 00:10:46.420
and burn only the
tips of the sticks

00:10:46.420 --> 00:10:48.590
as they enter the
combustion chamber.

00:10:48.590 --> 00:10:52.820
This is analogous to avoiding
burning too lean or too rich

00:10:52.820 --> 00:10:55.480
in a gasoline engine.

00:10:55.480 --> 00:10:59.940
Number five, design the stove
to maintain high-air velocity

00:10:59.940 --> 00:11:02.770
through the system.

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:05.880
And number five, do not
allow too much or too little

00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:08.520
air to enter the
combustion chamber.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:11.950
Strive to have a stoichiometric,
or a chemically ideal,

00:11:11.950 --> 00:11:13.210
combustion.

00:11:13.210 --> 00:11:16.870
This can best be achieved
by not jamming the fuel

00:11:16.870 --> 00:11:18.230
slot with wood.

00:11:18.230 --> 00:11:20.320
Too much fuel blocks air flow.

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:22.500
And it causes
incomplete combustion.

00:11:22.500 --> 00:11:24.190
And it produces smoke.

00:11:27.090 --> 00:11:30.930
Number six, maintain
constant cross-sectional area

00:11:30.930 --> 00:11:34.245
throughout the stove to
eliminate bottlenecks.

00:11:34.245 --> 00:11:37.290
And number seven,
elevate the fuel.

00:11:37.290 --> 00:11:40.150
And distribute air
flow around the fuel.

00:11:40.150 --> 00:11:42.330
The stove works best
when the fuel added

00:11:42.330 --> 00:11:47.570
is separated by a shelf
that allows this air flow.

00:11:47.570 --> 00:11:52.570
Number eight, use a grate under
the stove, under the fuel,

00:11:52.570 --> 00:11:55.260
so that the air flows
through the coals.

00:11:55.260 --> 00:11:57.910
Traditional stoves--
open fires that

00:11:57.910 --> 00:12:00.450
have fuel resting on
the ground-- experience

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:05.720
difficulty achieving the
correct mix of air and fuel.

00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:09.150
Number nine, insulate
the heat-flow path

00:12:09.150 --> 00:12:11.680
to and around the
cooking surfaces.

00:12:11.680 --> 00:12:16.110
As you can see, in this and in
most household rocket stoves,

00:12:16.110 --> 00:12:18.470
this is only partially achieved.

00:12:18.470 --> 00:12:21.300
The heat-flow path to
the pot is insulated,

00:12:21.300 --> 00:12:25.160
but not beyond the bottom
of the cooking surface.

00:12:25.160 --> 00:12:27.550
And finally, number
ten, optimize

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:30.130
the gaps around the
cooking surfaces

00:12:30.130 --> 00:12:34.700
to maximize heat transfer
without slowing down the draft.

00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:36.790
The supports that
elevate the pot

00:12:36.790 --> 00:12:39.540
above the stove in this
kind of rocket stove

00:12:39.540 --> 00:12:42.380
create the most critical
gap, where the heat transfer

00:12:42.380 --> 00:12:46.060
is reduced if the
gap is too small.

00:12:46.060 --> 00:12:47.950
If it's too large,
and a choke point

00:12:47.950 --> 00:12:50.250
is created if the
gap is too small.

00:12:50.250 --> 00:12:53.234
And it makes a smoky fire.

00:12:53.234 --> 00:12:55.600
Now, Damon took these
principles and applied them

00:12:55.600 --> 00:12:58.930
to designing an
institutional cook stove.

00:12:58.930 --> 00:13:03.910
And what he ended up with was
a stove that looks like this.

00:13:03.910 --> 00:13:06.300
Now, this stove's
been designed to best

00:13:06.300 --> 00:13:09.000
run on small amounts
of small wood--

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.970
little sticks that can
be sustainably harvested.

00:13:12.970 --> 00:13:16.140
In contrast, open-fire
cooking for institutions

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:19.240
tends to require large
amounts of large wood

00:13:19.240 --> 00:13:23.970
to generate enough heat energy
for the large pots they use.

00:13:23.970 --> 00:13:26.020
Most of this energy is wasted.

00:13:26.020 --> 00:13:27.860
A really efficient
three-stone fire

00:13:27.860 --> 00:13:32.220
is, at best, only about
15% thermally efficient.

00:13:32.220 --> 00:13:38.140
That means 85% of the heat
energy never reaches the pot.

00:13:38.140 --> 00:13:42.380
Our stove, from the moment
heat energy is generated,

00:13:42.380 --> 00:13:45.780
forces heated air to flow
up through the stove,

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:49.340
following a path that
provides maximum opportunity

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:52.850
for heat exchange with
the cooking surfaces

00:13:52.850 --> 00:13:56.760
to the bottom of the pot, and
then along its sides as well.

00:13:56.760 --> 00:14:00.060
Additional heat is retained
in the stove in this chamber

00:14:00.060 --> 00:14:03.620
by the metal skirt,
or the pot surround.

00:14:03.620 --> 00:14:06.980
As gases descend into
another insulated space,

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:10.510
we improve efficiency
with retained heat.

00:14:10.510 --> 00:14:15.200
Then those gases exit the stove
through the external chimney.

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:17.770
This design creates
an optimum draft,

00:14:17.770 --> 00:14:20.670
which pulls the heat
at a constant velocity

00:14:20.670 --> 00:14:23.270
through the system.

00:14:23.270 --> 00:14:28.190
With this stove, we have
reached 50% thermal efficiency.

00:14:28.190 --> 00:14:32.270
By way of contrast, the average
internal combustion engine

00:14:32.270 --> 00:14:34.970
is about 20% percent efficient.

00:14:34.970 --> 00:14:40.120
And the Prius we drove down here
today is about 40% efficient.

00:14:40.120 --> 00:14:43.000
With this stove, we get
more work out of wood

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.755
than modern combustion
engines get out of gasoline.

00:14:49.080 --> 00:14:53.280
In 2007, when Damon
first began designing

00:14:53.280 --> 00:14:56.330
what he was calling
a barrel stove,

00:14:56.330 --> 00:14:59.110
Dr. Winiarski, the
father of rocket stoves,

00:14:59.110 --> 00:15:01.440
was also working at Aprovecho.

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:04.180
And Larry had a
drawing of a design

00:15:04.180 --> 00:15:08.120
for an institutional stove that
didn't have a metal combustion

00:15:08.120 --> 00:15:10.480
chamber.

00:15:10.480 --> 00:15:13.340
At the time, the
conventional wisdom

00:15:13.340 --> 00:15:16.290
was, you can't use metal to
build rocket stove combustion

00:15:16.290 --> 00:15:17.750
chambers.

00:15:17.750 --> 00:15:21.410
But Damon was stubborn,
as engineers who are right

00:15:21.410 --> 00:15:23.710
sometimes can be.

00:15:23.710 --> 00:15:27.000
And he said, everyone thought
ceramic was the way to go.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:30.770
But my experiments keep showing
that the best results came out

00:15:30.770 --> 00:15:33.430
of a metal combustion chamber.

00:15:33.430 --> 00:15:36.080
So Damon designed his
metal combustion chamber,

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:40.350
and wanted to build and
test his barrel stoves

00:15:40.350 --> 00:15:44.100
in the field, where the
experiment would do some good.

00:15:44.100 --> 00:15:49.680
So he soon found a place
that needed some stoves.

00:15:49.680 --> 00:15:51.530
At the time, our
friend Ken Goyer

00:15:51.530 --> 00:15:56.220
had just started Aid Africa, a
nonprofit in northern Uganda,

00:15:56.220 --> 00:15:59.860
where the Lord's Resistance
Army, led by Joseph Kony,

00:15:59.860 --> 00:16:02.660
was terrorizing the region.

00:16:02.660 --> 00:16:05.280
Damon traveled there in 2007.

00:16:05.280 --> 00:16:07.720
And he brought with him
through customs a dozen

00:16:07.720 --> 00:16:09.590
different combustion
chambers, each

00:16:09.590 --> 00:16:13.460
made from different
high-temperature alloys not

00:16:13.460 --> 00:16:16.080
available in African markets.

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:19.700
And Damon trained a
team of local workers

00:16:19.700 --> 00:16:24.420
to build this first 12 prototype
stoves using local pots,

00:16:24.420 --> 00:16:26.334
and local parts.

00:16:26.334 --> 00:16:28.000
But used the combustion
chambers that he

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:32.000
had brought to make a variety
of field-testing prototypes.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:35.180
He placed the stoves in
several institutions,

00:16:35.180 --> 00:16:39.100
including the Laroo School
for War-Affected Children.

00:16:39.100 --> 00:16:41.300
And a year later, he
came back to measure

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:44.530
how the different combustion
chambers had worked, and held

00:16:44.530 --> 00:16:48.270
up when put through
rigorous daily use.

00:16:48.270 --> 00:16:50.960
When he returned to
Oregon after this,

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:53.680
to design the first
60-liter stoves,

00:16:53.680 --> 00:16:57.440
that's when I met up with him.

00:16:57.440 --> 00:16:59.450
Now, Damon and I hit
it off pretty quick,

00:16:59.450 --> 00:17:02.700
and realized we shared
a passion to serve,

00:17:02.700 --> 00:17:06.230
and a vision of realistic
approaches to the development

00:17:06.230 --> 00:17:09.020
and the proliferation
of technology

00:17:09.020 --> 00:17:11.560
to serve the world's
poorest people.

00:17:11.560 --> 00:17:13.890
We continue our
close collaboration.

00:17:13.890 --> 00:17:17.300
And Damon today still directs
our research and development

00:17:17.300 --> 00:17:18.109
department.

00:17:18.109 --> 00:17:23.569
And I head up the day-to-day
operations of our organization.

00:17:23.569 --> 00:17:27.970
In 2008 and 2009, we continued
testing and tinkering

00:17:27.970 --> 00:17:30.295
and improving Damon's model.

00:17:30.295 --> 00:17:32.380
And our first
break came in 2010,

00:17:32.380 --> 00:17:35.730
when the German international
cooperation and aid

00:17:35.730 --> 00:17:39.330
agency called GIZ
asked us to do a pilot

00:17:39.330 --> 00:17:44.150
project with 60-liter stoves
in a girls' school in Bita,

00:17:44.150 --> 00:17:45.095
in northern Nigeria.

00:17:47.750 --> 00:17:51.370
The Bita Girls Secondary
School is an amazing place,

00:17:51.370 --> 00:17:55.800
a school with 1,600
female students, divided

00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:58.040
between Muslim and
Christians, where

00:17:58.040 --> 00:18:00.960
there are no
religious conflicts.

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:04.630
And I traveled there in 2010,
and installed three stoves,

00:18:04.630 --> 00:18:09.410
which reduced the school's
fuel costs by 75%.

00:18:09.410 --> 00:18:11.460
The stoves were so
efficient that they

00:18:11.460 --> 00:18:15.480
paid for the installation
in seven months.

00:18:15.480 --> 00:18:17.480
Four years later,
these three stoves

00:18:17.480 --> 00:18:21.580
are still providing the
food for the 1,600 students.

00:18:21.580 --> 00:18:24.280
And the head cook,
Hajia Ishmael,

00:18:24.280 --> 00:18:26.460
the woman who brought
her infant son with her

00:18:26.460 --> 00:18:30.290
to work on her back every
day, shared this with me.

00:18:30.290 --> 00:18:33.550
"With the new stoves,
my eyes don't water.

00:18:33.550 --> 00:18:35.170
My chest doesn't hurt.

00:18:35.170 --> 00:18:36.960
My back doesn't ache.

00:18:36.960 --> 00:18:41.770
And the baby on my back
has stopped crying."

00:18:41.770 --> 00:18:46.700
This project was so successful,
we soon had an order in hand

00:18:46.700 --> 00:18:49.610
from a UN agency for
200 stoves for Darfur.

00:18:52.860 --> 00:18:57.760
Since 2010, we've placed over
1,000 stoves in 25 countries,

00:18:57.760 --> 00:19:00.880
including 15 countries
in sub-Saharan Africa.

00:19:04.820 --> 00:19:07.150
Damon and I agreed
early on that bringing

00:19:07.150 --> 00:19:09.940
not just the technology,
but the production of stoves

00:19:09.940 --> 00:19:12.610
to a country-- just like
he had done in Uganda--

00:19:12.610 --> 00:19:14.660
was the ultimate goal.

00:19:14.660 --> 00:19:17.290
So we developed a
stove production method

00:19:17.290 --> 00:19:20.680
to be replicable,
and created a method

00:19:20.680 --> 00:19:24.100
we call Stove Factory in a Box.

00:19:24.100 --> 00:19:27.820
Now, in this model, we put
all the materials and tools

00:19:27.820 --> 00:19:31.450
necessary to build our stoves
into a shipping container.

00:19:31.450 --> 00:19:35.500
We ship this container
to an in-country partner.

00:19:35.500 --> 00:19:38.230
And then, following the
arrival of the container,

00:19:38.230 --> 00:19:41.110
we send a team of
InStove's stove builders

00:19:41.110 --> 00:19:43.510
to teach local workers
how to replicate

00:19:43.510 --> 00:19:45.780
our manufacturing process.

00:19:45.780 --> 00:19:49.450
What we found in our research
and development of the stove

00:19:49.450 --> 00:19:52.540
was that the difference
of the few millimeters

00:19:52.540 --> 00:19:56.540
could cost 15% or 20%
percent in efficiency.

00:19:56.540 --> 00:19:59.470
Our stoves require
precision manufacturing.

00:19:59.470 --> 00:20:02.670
So we designed our
system to force precision

00:20:02.670 --> 00:20:06.910
through the use of custom jigs
and very exacting standards.

00:20:06.910 --> 00:20:09.900
Our factory runs
on minimal energy,

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:12.480
and can easily be powered
by the few tasks that

00:20:12.480 --> 00:20:14.920
require electricity
with a small generator.

00:20:18.020 --> 00:20:20.520
By transferring our
tools and know-how,

00:20:20.520 --> 00:20:23.520
we can train in-country
workers to build stoves

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:27.040
to our precise
one-millimeter tolerances.

00:20:27.040 --> 00:20:29.090
And with Stove
Factory in a Box, we

00:20:29.090 --> 00:20:33.530
can bring production
anywhere in the world.

00:20:33.530 --> 00:20:36.260
Our goal for each country
where we are needed

00:20:36.260 --> 00:20:38.850
is to begin with
small pilot projects,

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:42.350
and then bring a larger number
of stoves for market testing.

00:20:42.350 --> 00:20:44.440
And then, if there's
sufficient demand,

00:20:44.440 --> 00:20:47.420
we explore partnerships
and pursue funding

00:20:47.420 --> 00:20:50.080
to open a factory in-country.

00:20:50.080 --> 00:20:52.840
By opening these
local factories,

00:20:52.840 --> 00:20:55.070
we create living-wage jobs.

00:20:55.070 --> 00:20:57.660
We increase local
economic independence.

00:20:57.660 --> 00:21:03.150
And we make our stove
initiative truly sustainable.

00:21:03.150 --> 00:21:04.870
By now, you may be
wondering, well,

00:21:04.870 --> 00:21:07.590
how good are our stoves, really?

00:21:07.590 --> 00:21:09.310
From the beginning,
and for seven years,

00:21:09.310 --> 00:21:13.410
we've continued to improve our
design, testing it in the lab

00:21:13.410 --> 00:21:15.840
and in the field.

00:21:15.840 --> 00:21:17.650
And now, our stoves
are independently

00:21:17.650 --> 00:21:20.410
verified by third-party
testing labs

00:21:20.410 --> 00:21:23.400
and by hundreds of
users in the field

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:27.720
to consistently accomplish
the following results.

00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:31.760
They reduce carbon monoxide and
particulate matter emissions

00:21:31.760 --> 00:21:34.120
by 90%.

00:21:34.120 --> 00:21:38.320
They cut fuel use by 75%-90%.

00:21:38.320 --> 00:21:41.580
And they reduce cooking
time by 50% or more.

00:21:44.750 --> 00:21:48.160
The International
Standards Organization

00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:52.150
has an International
Workshop Agreement, or IWA,

00:21:52.150 --> 00:21:55.870
that's measuring clean cook
stoves in 11 categories,

00:21:55.870 --> 00:22:00.170
or indicators, that are ranked
on a scale from one to four,

00:22:00.170 --> 00:22:02.860
with four being the
highest ranking.

00:22:02.860 --> 00:22:05.410
In nine out of
these 11 indicators,

00:22:05.410 --> 00:22:08.270
our stoves are ranked four.

00:22:08.270 --> 00:22:11.770
These indicators primarily
measure emissions-- including

00:22:11.770 --> 00:22:15.210
carbon monoxide and
particulate matter-- produced

00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:18.000
at both high and low powers.

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:20.280
In the world of
stoves, high power

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:24.150
means the power you need to
bring a pot of food to a boil,

00:22:24.150 --> 00:22:26.550
or a pot of water to
a boil in the lab.

00:22:26.550 --> 00:22:28.320
And low power means
the amount you

00:22:28.320 --> 00:22:31.370
need to keep it
simmering as you cook.

00:22:34.620 --> 00:22:37.850
In our stove, the temperatures
within the combustion chamber

00:22:37.850 --> 00:22:40.990
reach up to 1,150
degrees Celsius.

00:22:40.990 --> 00:22:43.320
That's over 2,000
degrees Fahrenheit.

00:22:43.320 --> 00:22:46.620
And our stove is burning so
hot that it literally burns up

00:22:46.620 --> 00:22:48.740
the smoke.

00:22:48.740 --> 00:22:52.650
But how does this
compare to other stoves?

00:22:52.650 --> 00:22:54.760
This chart, completed
by researchers

00:22:54.760 --> 00:22:58.000
across the bay at the
Berkeley Air Monitoring Group,

00:22:58.000 --> 00:23:01.560
compare particular matter
and carbon monoxide produced

00:23:01.560 --> 00:23:04.750
at high power in
different kinds of stoves,

00:23:04.750 --> 00:23:07.070
including charcoal
stoves and pellet

00:23:07.070 --> 00:23:11.220
stoves, fan-driven stoves that
require electricity, chimney

00:23:11.220 --> 00:23:16.360
stoves, and griddle stoves, and,
finally, liquid or gas stoves.

00:23:16.360 --> 00:23:21.290
And our institutional
rocket stove tests here.

00:23:21.290 --> 00:23:23.080
This puts our stove
two categories

00:23:23.080 --> 00:23:26.710
above household rocket stoves.

00:23:26.710 --> 00:23:30.810
And it puts it nearly on a level
as clean burning as liquid fuel

00:23:30.810 --> 00:23:32.410
or gas stoves.

00:23:32.410 --> 00:23:34.840
The only way to
improve our performance

00:23:34.840 --> 00:23:37.360
would be to change the fuel.

00:23:37.360 --> 00:23:40.450
And until natural gas
or LPG grows on trees,

00:23:40.450 --> 00:23:44.010
it probably isn't a
viable alternative.

00:23:44.010 --> 00:23:46.400
As to cost
effectiveness, our stoves

00:23:46.400 --> 00:23:48.890
are so efficient
that in fuel savings,

00:23:48.890 --> 00:23:51.980
they pay for themselves, in
most cases, in just over a year

00:23:51.980 --> 00:23:52.630
of use.

00:23:55.600 --> 00:23:57.210
Here, you can see
our stove being

00:23:57.210 --> 00:24:00.750
used alongside some really
rudimentary improved stoves

00:24:00.750 --> 00:24:02.300
in Senegal.

00:24:02.300 --> 00:24:04.550
When we set up our
stove to cook here,

00:24:04.550 --> 00:24:06.980
we couldn't find any
small wood prepared,

00:24:06.980 --> 00:24:11.470
because they use large wood to
heat their large pots of food.

00:24:11.470 --> 00:24:13.440
So we had to find--
the smallest stick

00:24:13.440 --> 00:24:17.530
we could find was this one you
see jammed into the fuel slot.

00:24:17.530 --> 00:24:21.190
Our stoves run best on
small amounts of small wood

00:24:21.190 --> 00:24:23.620
that can be
sustainably harvested

00:24:23.620 --> 00:24:27.390
without destroying whole trees.

00:24:27.390 --> 00:24:30.170
But our stoves do
more than cook.

00:24:30.170 --> 00:24:33.140
Institutional stoves
produce much more firepower

00:24:33.140 --> 00:24:34.340
than other stoves.

00:24:34.340 --> 00:24:40.000
And this energy can be harnessed
for additional applications.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:44.720
Our 100-liter stove works with a
gravity-fed, flow-through water

00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:48.120
pasteurizer of our own design.

00:24:48.120 --> 00:24:50.220
And this pasteurizer
can produce over

00:24:50.220 --> 00:24:53.490
200 gallons of potable
water per hour,

00:24:53.490 --> 00:24:55.690
using just a pencil's
weight of wood--

00:24:55.690 --> 00:24:59.660
about five grams for
each liter produced.

00:24:59.660 --> 00:25:03.080
We field-tested this
pasteurizer in the Zambia

00:25:03.080 --> 00:25:05.540
in October of 2013.

00:25:05.540 --> 00:25:08.130
And in the field,
just as in the lab,

00:25:08.130 --> 00:25:14.060
the pasteurizer eliminates
100% of water-borne pathogens.

00:25:14.060 --> 00:25:16.270
With the support of
the Geisse Foundation,

00:25:16.270 --> 00:25:20.390
we're now in the research phase
of creating a high-flow sand

00:25:20.390 --> 00:25:24.670
filter that will allow us to
address the issue of turbidity,

00:25:24.670 --> 00:25:27.350
of particulate
matter in the water.

00:25:27.350 --> 00:25:29.280
With this upstream
filter, we'll be

00:25:29.280 --> 00:25:31.360
able to filter out
solids, and make

00:25:31.360 --> 00:25:35.860
water look as clean and
safe as it really is.

00:25:35.860 --> 00:25:39.430
We're exploring partnerships
to implement this technology

00:25:39.430 --> 00:25:42.300
as part of rural
micro utilities that

00:25:42.300 --> 00:25:45.860
can provide clean water
and sanitation and hygiene

00:25:45.860 --> 00:25:46.900
trainings.

00:25:46.900 --> 00:25:50.130
And we're looking
at this pasteurizer

00:25:50.130 --> 00:25:53.010
as the basis of
a micro business,

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:54.060
providing clean water.

00:25:59.230 --> 00:26:02.330
Our 60-liter stove
is also paired

00:26:02.330 --> 00:26:05.990
with an autoclave that can
sterilize medical equipment,

00:26:05.990 --> 00:26:09.820
making use of supplies
like bandages, dressings,

00:26:09.820 --> 00:26:11.190
and scalpels.

00:26:11.190 --> 00:26:12.010
It's OK, Assitan.

00:26:12.010 --> 00:26:13.560
Yeah, you want to do that?

00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:15.530
OK.

00:26:15.530 --> 00:26:18.120
Bandages, dressings,
scalpels, needles

00:26:18.120 --> 00:26:21.430
can be safe for reuse or
for hygienic disposal,

00:26:21.430 --> 00:26:23.666
in accordance with
international medical standards.

00:26:28.530 --> 00:26:32.480
This ensemble is already saving
lives in Kenya, and Chad,

00:26:32.480 --> 00:26:36.900
and Zambia, and the Democratic
Republic of the Congo.

00:26:36.900 --> 00:26:38.780
Thank you.

00:26:38.780 --> 00:26:41.930
And we just completed a
pilot project in Kathmandu

00:26:41.930 --> 00:26:45.250
that will introduce our
autoclave to rural clinics

00:26:45.250 --> 00:26:49.730
across Nepal and help
remote centers there arrive

00:26:49.730 --> 00:26:54.190
at international standards in
their waste-disposal practices.

00:26:54.190 --> 00:26:58.780
This pilot project also
represents our first entry

00:26:58.780 --> 00:27:00.180
into Asian markets.

00:27:02.900 --> 00:27:04.810
Because all of our
technologies have

00:27:04.810 --> 00:27:07.120
been designed to
work off the grid,

00:27:07.120 --> 00:27:10.360
they're ideal for use in
settings where electricity

00:27:10.360 --> 00:27:15.240
and modern fuels are scarce,
or unavailable-- places

00:27:15.240 --> 00:27:19.430
like rural hospitals and
clinics, or refugee camps,

00:27:19.430 --> 00:27:21.825
or in disaster-relief
situations.

00:27:24.410 --> 00:27:27.820
We have a long list
of R&amp;D projects,

00:27:27.820 --> 00:27:31.370
intending to use the stove
for additional applications.

00:27:31.370 --> 00:27:36.050
On our list are a bread oven,
a water pump, a refrigeration

00:27:36.050 --> 00:27:38.590
system, and a
cell-phone charging

00:27:38.590 --> 00:27:40.880
station, all powered
by the InStove.

00:27:45.810 --> 00:27:48.000
We're a nonprofit organization.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:50.680
And we raise funds from
philanthropic donors,

00:27:50.680 --> 00:27:53.640
and sell stoves to
support our mission.

00:27:53.640 --> 00:27:56.550
With the importance of
the problems we solve,

00:27:56.550 --> 00:27:59.230
and the effectiveness
with which we do it,

00:27:59.230 --> 00:28:01.090
it might at first
seem hard to believe

00:28:01.090 --> 00:28:04.570
that funding and clients
are difficult to both find

00:28:04.570 --> 00:28:05.770
and maintain.

00:28:05.770 --> 00:28:10.710
But the markets for stoves
face many challenges, not least

00:28:10.710 --> 00:28:15.280
of which is the volatility
of funding cycles.

00:28:15.280 --> 00:28:19.580
Our strategy for growth is to
build strategic partnerships

00:28:19.580 --> 00:28:24.530
with agencies small and
large throughout the world.

00:28:24.530 --> 00:28:28.360
Getting life-changing
technology to the world's poor

00:28:28.360 --> 00:28:30.570
is why we exist.

00:28:30.570 --> 00:28:35.650
Our mission is to improve
health, to enhance safety,

00:28:35.650 --> 00:28:38.120
and to reduce harm
to the environment

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:42.210
through the design, the
manufacture, and the delivery

00:28:42.210 --> 00:28:47.350
of highly efficient stoves
and allied technologies

00:28:47.350 --> 00:28:49.925
to the most vulnerable
populations worldwide.

00:28:52.450 --> 00:28:57.150
We joined the larger unified
fight against indoor pollution

00:28:57.150 --> 00:29:01.090
as members of the Global
Alliance for Clean Cook Stoves.

00:29:01.090 --> 00:29:02.910
It's a public-private
partnership,

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:07.040
led by the United
Nations Foundation.

00:29:07.040 --> 00:29:09.050
The Global Alliance
was born in 2010,

00:29:09.050 --> 00:29:13.880
when then-Secretary of State
Hillary Clinton and a range

00:29:13.880 --> 00:29:17.050
of leading international
public and private figures

00:29:17.050 --> 00:29:21.180
launched it, with the ambitious
mission of transforming

00:29:21.180 --> 00:29:23.380
the global market
for clean cook stoves

00:29:23.380 --> 00:29:26.090
and fuels with a
specific goal of spurring

00:29:26.090 --> 00:29:30.350
the adoption of clean cook
stoves and fuels in 100

00:29:30.350 --> 00:29:34.710
million households by 2020.

00:29:34.710 --> 00:29:36.720
The Global Alliance
is leading the way

00:29:36.720 --> 00:29:39.570
in raising consciousness
around this issue.

00:29:39.570 --> 00:29:41.960
And I think they said it best.

00:29:41.960 --> 00:29:45.510
"While some may think that the
poor cannot afford to adopt

00:29:45.510 --> 00:29:50.160
clean cooking technologies, the
opposite is, in fact, the case.

