It's much more complicated
than institutional cooking.

00:45:01.960 --> 00:45:08.020
Household stoves need to be
designed for very low prices

00:45:08.020 --> 00:45:09.630
to accomplish a lot.

00:45:09.630 --> 00:45:14.990
And then they need to
be adopted by women,

00:45:14.990 --> 00:45:18.370
whose primary interest
is that the food tastes

00:45:18.370 --> 00:45:20.740
like their grandma's
food tasted.

00:45:20.740 --> 00:45:23.660
And that's very tricky to
do, to change technologies.

00:45:23.660 --> 00:45:28.080
So it's been-- it's
an ongoing challenge

00:45:28.080 --> 00:45:32.860
to convince women to change
their cooking habits to adopt

00:45:32.860 --> 00:45:34.550
more modern stoves.

00:45:34.550 --> 00:45:37.120
And also, to come up with
the money to pay for them.

00:45:37.120 --> 00:45:42.300
It's-- at $10 or $15 or $20,
that's a very expensive stove

00:45:42.300 --> 00:45:43.540
in African markets.

00:45:43.540 --> 00:45:46.620
And it's very hard to
deliver an industrial product

00:45:46.620 --> 00:45:48.440
for those kind of prices.

00:45:48.440 --> 00:45:52.510
So, like I said, there
are many players.

00:45:52.510 --> 00:45:56.170
We're focused on institutions.

00:45:56.170 --> 00:45:58.640
And we're going to let
our colleagues address

00:45:58.640 --> 00:46:01.110
the household cooking issue.

00:46:01.110 --> 00:46:03.770
We may get drawn into
that at some point.

00:46:03.770 --> 00:46:08.980
But for the moment, we're
going to stay focused.

00:46:08.980 --> 00:46:13.530
The challenges are huge--
logistical challenges.

00:46:13.530 --> 00:46:19.560
To get stoves from Oregon
to anywhere in Africa,

00:46:19.560 --> 00:46:21.430
there are all kinds of
issues that come up.

00:46:21.430 --> 00:46:26.690
Just the raw logistics of
getting shipments into country

00:46:26.690 --> 00:46:30.150
through customs,
past corruption,

00:46:30.150 --> 00:46:35.110
and into the hands of
users is very challenging.

00:46:35.110 --> 00:46:37.620
Finding funding sources,
finding agencies

00:46:37.620 --> 00:46:39.820
who can afford
the stoves and can

00:46:39.820 --> 00:46:43.260
afford to participate in
development is very tricky.

00:46:46.500 --> 00:46:49.260
There are a host of
problems-- host of challenges,

00:46:49.260 --> 00:46:51.420
I would say.

00:46:51.420 --> 00:46:52.590
We're still overcoming them.

00:46:52.590 --> 00:46:55.180
We're learning to overcome them.

00:46:55.180 --> 00:46:58.900
We have a container of stoves
arriving this week in Kampala,

00:46:58.900 --> 00:47:02.080
in Uganda, for a
wider distribution.

00:47:02.080 --> 00:47:05.350
So that's the second tier
of our development strategy.

00:47:05.350 --> 00:47:06.310
We're learning.

00:47:06.310 --> 00:47:07.970
We're a small organization.

00:47:07.970 --> 00:47:12.750
Some of my team are absolutely
fantastic at logistics--

00:47:12.750 --> 00:47:20.110
and now, increasingly, at
developing markets in Africa.

00:47:20.110 --> 00:47:23.690
AUDIENCE: What is the
lifetime for a stove?

00:47:23.690 --> 00:47:26.600
FRED COLGAN: Well, when we
started, we weren't sure.

00:47:26.600 --> 00:47:30.330
We've had stoves in the
field now for four years,

00:47:30.330 --> 00:47:33.240
with almost zero failure rate.

00:47:33.240 --> 00:47:35.630
So we're waiting for
that first failure point.

00:47:35.630 --> 00:47:39.250
We think somewhere in
year five, year six,

00:47:39.250 --> 00:47:41.850
we're going to see some
deterioration of some

00:47:41.850 --> 00:47:44.000
of the parts.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:47.470
But these are
interchangeable parts.

00:47:47.470 --> 00:47:51.740
So with maintenance, we're
confident a ten-year lifespan

00:47:51.740 --> 00:47:54.830
is possible, and maybe longer.

00:47:54.830 --> 00:47:59.250
The only stoves that have failed
have been left out in the rain.

00:47:59.250 --> 00:48:02.520
So we're looking at a
very, very long livelihood

00:48:02.520 --> 00:48:04.500
for these stoves.

00:48:04.500 --> 00:48:06.140
I want to thank you for coming.

00:48:06.140 --> 00:48:08.950
